/**
 * Fetches user profile data with an integrated local storage cache layer.
 * 
 * @param {string|number} userId - The unique identifier for the user.
 * @param {boolean} [forceRefresh=false] - If true, bypasses the local cache.
 * @returns {Promise<Object>} The parsed user profile data.
 */
async function fetchUserProfile(userId, forceRefresh = false) {
  const cacheKey = `user_${userId}`;
  
  if (!forceRefresh) {
    const cachedData = localStorage.getItem(cacheKey);
    if (cachedData) {
      return JSON.parse(cachedData);
    }
  }

  try {
    const response = await fetch(`https://api.example.com/users/${userId}`);
    
    if (!response.ok) {
      throw new Error(`HTTP error! status: ${response.status}`);
    }

    const userData = await response.json();
    localStorage.setItem(cacheKey, JSON.stringify(userData));
    return userData;
    
  } catch (error) {
    // Log internally but re-throw so the caller knows the operation failed
    console.error(`Failed to fetch profile for user ${userId}:`, error);
    throw error; 
  }
}

/**
 * The Danger of "Swallowing" Promises
Logging an error via console.log(err) inside a catch block without re-throwing it is a critical anti-pattern. To JavaScript, a caught error that does not explicitly throw is considered "handled," which implicitly resolves the parent Promise with a value of undefined. This forces your calling UI components to crash downstream when they try to read property fields that don't exist, rather than allowing them to gracefully catch the failure and render an error state.

II. Designing Boundaries via Decoupling
A data-fetching utility should have single-minded focus: transport, translate, and cache data. Introducing environmental side effects like a browser-native alert() breaks portability. If that same utility needs to be run in a backend test suite, a server-side rendering (SSR) environment, or a native worker context, the execution environment will instantly throw a fatal error. Keep your transport functions pure; let the UI component catching the output decide how to present the error state to the end user.

III. Linear Code is Maintainable Code
Asynchronous callback structures (.then().catch()) inherently force your eyes to trace a zigzag path across the screen, adding massive cognitive load. Transitioning to an async/await pattern wrapped in a native try/catch block allows developers to read complex network orchestration code linearly—exactly like traditional synchronous code. When code is written to be read from top to bottom, spotting logical fallacies becomes significantly easier.





